\'93Grounding data-rich literary history in scholarly editions of literary systems emphasizes that constructing literary data is just as much an interpretive and critical activity as its analysis and that the nuance of such analyses foundationally depends on the historical knowledge embedded in those constructions. With a scholarly edition of a literary system already, in and of itself, an argument about a \'93collective system\'a0.\'a0.\'a0. as a whole\'94 (Moretti, Graphs 4), analyses of it can attend to the multiple features and dimensions it models. Alan Liu\'92s notion of \'93contingency\'94 encapsulates the resulting analytic mode. Describing the relationship of historicism to the database, Liu notes that in neither form does one ask what is this whole, what does it mean? Rather, the question becomes 
\b how does this complex system I am investigating appear from this perspective?
\b0  Although the whole is composed of parts that are explicitly defined and constrained\'97\'93chained to context,\'94 as Liu puts it\'97the mode of inquiry it supports is transactional, enabling unpredictable connections and insights (Local 262).\
As with a scholarly edition of a literary work, a
\b  scholarly edition of a literary system is thus intended not to conclude but to support various forms of investigation
\b0 , including those that move between the single literary work and the system in which it existed and operated\'94 (Bode 56)\
\
\'93The approach to data-rich literary history I am advocating 
\b does not take the path increasingly recommended for the field: of integrating scientific and social scientific measures of statistical uncertainty
\b0  into historical analysis (Goldstone, \'93Distant\'94). Given that constructing literary data is a historical argument made in the context of a history of transmission\'97the effects of which are difficult to qualify, let alone to quantify\'97
\b I do not see that any assessment of error is made more useful or concise by its numerical expression
\b0 . Instead, in the intersection of a critical apparatus and curated dataset, the framework of the scholarly edition offers a theoretical and practical basis to model the relationships of production and reception that constitute historical literary systems, while assessing and managing the inevitable contingency of those relationships and of the documentary infrastructure through which we perceive them.\'94 (Bode 57)\
\
\'93A model of a literary system is not only an argument about the historical nature and meaning of interconnections between literary works in the past. As chapter 2 explores, inevitably, it is also the outcome of a history of transmission: the many instances of production and reception, including the scholar\'92s acts of interpretation, by which evidence of those historical meanings and connections is apprehended and represented. A history of transmission constitutes the object analyzed in data-rich literary history and, therefore, a project\'92s capacity to advance understanding. I ended chapter 2 by outlining an object capable of describing that engagement and justifying and demonstrating its outcomes. Called a scholarly edition of a literary system, it is comprised of a curated dataset, offering a stable and accessible model of the existence and interconnections of literary works in the past, and a critical apparatus that reveals the hypothetical nature of that modeled literary system and establishes it as a reliable basis for analysis. Along with designated fields in the curated dataset, detailing decisions and arguments underpinning individual data constructions, the critical apparatus for the scholarly edition underpinning this book\'97of extended fiction in nineteenth-century Australian newspapers\'97is composed of a historical introduction, describing the Page 60 
\f1 \uc0\u8594 
\f0 broad features and effects of the history of transmission producing the modeled data.\'94 (Bode 59-60)}